## Context

Audit 0070 flagged bias **B8** (multiple comparisons) as ⚠. With 6
methods × ~22 years × 4 windows we run ≈ 528 pointwise tests. Under
pointwise α = 0.05 the global null expectation is ≈ 26 false positives.
The "≥ 2 channels above Z > 2 within a 2-year window" rule is a
correction-by-design but not a formal Type-I-error statement.

We need a single number — the joint Type I error for a validated
transition zone — so a reviewer can't push back on the multiple-
comparisons question without arithmetic.

## Actions

1. Add `scripts/compute_meta_null.py`: permute publication-year labels
   across the entire corpus (`n_perm = 500` or the existing config
   value), and for each realization run all six divergence channels with
   their default settings.
2. For each realization, record whether ≥ 2 channels exceed Z > 2 at
   the same year (within ±2 years). The empirical frequency over
   realizations is the joint Type I error.
3. Output: `content/tables/tab_meta_null_joint_alpha.csv` with
   `n_perm, joint_alpha_05, joint_alpha_01`.
4. One sentence for §4.8: "The probability that ≥ 2 channels jointly
   exceed Z > 2 at the same year under the global null is p = X.XX
   (500 permutations)."

## Test

`tests/test_meta_null.py::test_single_perm_end_to_end` — asserts one
meta-null permutation runs end-to-end for all six channels and returns a
boolean "jointly validated" flag. Red until the script exists.

## Exit criteria

- Meta-null Makefile target (`divergence.mk` or `null.mk`).
- Joint-alpha number cited in §4.8.
- Child of 0070 closed.

## Note on compute cost

This is 6 × n_perm full-pipeline runs. At ~30 s per channel per
permutation this is a few compute-hours; schedule on padme or in a
nightly job, not in `make check`.
